            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_BASE_CORE_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>A time-tested tool for mass oppression. The Tax Bureau is a dim-lit maze of dingy cubicles packed full of tired, irritable office dwellers that will likely never see the light of day. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited. The neologism Aura (Auras) is a good idea but I would avoid the term in this early stage and use something more general/comprehensive as founds or coins ...  -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_ECONOMY_UPGRADE1_LORE</LocID>                      <Text>Your base is growing, but so are tax evasion, corruption, and clandestine attempts to overthrow everything you've built. Never fear. A legion of bureaucrats from the Inner Control office can help track down missing loot and keep your coffers full.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_ECONOMY_UPGRADE2_LORE</LocID>                      <Text>The piercing eye of big brother sees all. It peers relentlessly for even a glint of resistance. When the Oversser's Office is out hunting traitors, even the hardest recalcitrants know to keep their hands out of the cookie jar or undermine the Supreme Leader's authority.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_ECONOMY_UPGRADE_MAX_LORE</LocID>                   <Text>Bureaucracy is fun, even efficient if you deploy an atmosphere of constant suspicion and mutual control. But only a singular tyrant, living a monk's life of service to the Supreme Leader can instill true fear and squeeze even the last bit of value from the exhausted masses.</Text></GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited: One more detail I would like to implement as I read the texts after a while. I would like to emphasize the non-critical consumption of facts by the Fossorian masses... something like "it's magically doubled its output".-->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_REPLICATOR_LORE</LocID>                            <Text>They named it Replicator. Its secret so jealously guarded by its select initiates that the masses believe it's magically doubled its output. Science, Mr. White! In truth, its growth is an illusion. Instead, it's stretched thin and diluted. No one cares about quality if the numbers add up.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited. When I read the new version "old Fossorian homeworld of Fossoria" the world Fossorian and Fossoria are somehow "too close" in the sentence. Let's end the sentence with "the old Fossorian homeworld." The name Fossoria will be mentioned elsewhere ;-). -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_GATEWAY_LORE</LocID>                               <Text>Underground travel is an absolute necessity on the old Fossorian homeworld. The planet's polluted surface is so dangerous and inhospitable that building a new tunnel to reach even faraway lands always pays off.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPACE_BAR_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Any traveler unlucky enough to find themselves in a Fossorian Space Bar soon realizes that the liquor tastes worse than industrial degreaser. Still, every Fossorian drinker knows that quantity always trumps quality. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_MUSIC_HALL_LORE</LocID>                            <Text>The Officers' Club is most definitely an improvement. Strangers, mercs, and all manner of adventurers "brave" enough to willingly enter a Fossorian base will probably be thrilled with the idea of becoming "military advisers".</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited. "are novel but alien concepts." alien is too strong here. Let's end the sentence with "are novel concepts." Sounds more like the concept is new but they are adopting the ideas to overcome the disadvantage of the new environment. -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_VISIBILITY_UPGRADE_LORE</LocID>                    <Text>Old Fossoria's surface is a wasteland scoured by meat-grinding storms. After centuries of sub-surface conflicts, a habitable topside and the need to see long distances are novel concepts. Still, let's build upward for once!</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited: I do believe that the part about the seal pups would make the text punchier if we move it back to the end of the text. Also, I would choose a more strait forward/brutal sentence. "No matter how many seal pups will perish." or a softer alternative "perishing seal pups is the last thing on their minds." -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_RECYCLER_LORE</LocID>                              <Text>Make no mistake, Fossorian recycling has nothing to do with saving the environment. They only wish to reclaim material to churn out even more gruesome weapons of destruction, no matter how many seal pups will perish.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited: "focuses exclusively on Force Shields" is not entirely what I meant... The sweatshop is a prerequisite for other buildings in the base (Production of Earthshaker Unit, a vehicle able to deploy underground torpedoes, overseers office)... the main benefit for the player though is shield generator production, so emphasis on put that but it is not the sole purpose. -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACTORY_LORE</LocID>                               <Text>The sweatshop once produced peacetime machinery but now focuses on military applications, especially Force Shields. The early days of colonization might have gone differently had they had shield technology. Well, they do now.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_TRADING_POST_LORE</LocID>                          <Text>It's forbidden for common citizens to access the broader market. There's no need. The base produces all the necessities and luxury goods they could want. Empty shelves? No worries! They'll be restocked tomorrow. Or the day after, surely. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_CORE_LORE</LocID>                        <Text>A giant stronghold with 5-meter-thick limerite-reinforced walls. It's packed to the gills with bunkers and fancy strategic meeting rooms. From recruitment drive schedules to combat shovel sizes, any and all war effort decisions get made here.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Edited. Let's divide the sentence more into two parts. The part about defense the building provides to the base and the part describing the roots of the revolution. "Additional defenses for the base and more..."  -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_TOWER_LORE</LocID>                       <Text>Additional defenses for the base and more space for the disenchanted, low-ranking officers. Some minimal creature comforts should prevent them from kindling another revolution like the one that brought the Fossorians from their homeworld to the Siren system.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>


            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_MINES_LORE</LocID>                       <Text>Humans have a saying "Where the foot of a Fossorian steps, grass will never grow again. Except for the patches where land mines lay hidden." Despite the brief time both races have shared in a single solar system, this is actually pretty accurate.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_ACADEMY_LORE</LocID>                               <Text>The Supreme Leader once said, "There is no need for science if it does not contribute to the war effort". So any scientific endeavor must have a military application. No matter how obscure. Acid-squirting wristwatch? Instant approval. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_REMOTE_LEARNING_LORE</LocID>                       <Text>A Neurolink, implanted in the spinal cord, assures a reasonably stable one-way connection. (Even in the jammer-filled telecommunication nightmare of the Siren system.)</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACULTY_SPECIALIZATION_LORE</LocID>                <Text>During any conquest, many things change owners. Sometimes those things are people. Highly intelligent people can find a home in a Fossorian research facility in exchange for the sum of their knowledge.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: Question: Chris, I would like to ask which one is more appropriate, sounds better in your opinion. High Party members or Inner Party members? I associate the High Party with more modern politics but the Inner Party is much more Orwellian.  -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACULTY_EXPLORE_LORE</LocID>                       <Text>Some privileged children of inner party members founded the Club for Explorers and Adventurers. Most of its members are utterly useless, but a select few are seasoned travelers capable of teaching a newcomer a helpful trick or two.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JU: A new suggested version, we know it needs editing :) -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACULTY_TECH_LORE</LocID>                          <Text>The Fossorian homeworld is so uninhabitable you'd think it suffered a natural cataclysm. There was indeed an apocalypse, but we can exclude natural causes. (Unless you count the Fossorians - who hold the title for the most doomsday devices ever deployed - as a natural cause.)</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!--  JU: Edited. I would like to return to the original phrasing "A broad face with **heavy** black whiskers and ruggedly..." as it's a direct reference for my great inspiration, Orwels 1984: "the face of a man of about forty-five, with a heavy black moustache and ruggedly handsome features" -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_CREATURE_PRODUCTION_UPGRADE_1_LORE</LocID>         <Text>A broad face with heavy black whiskers and ruggedly handsome features. Everyone knows, fears, and loves the Supreme Leader. His reassuring features tell the whole base that everything is going according to plan.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_1_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>The birthplace of the lowest rung of Fossarian society. No one cares what happens in this slum brimming with mindless, filthy crossbreeds. All that matters is the neverending stream of fresh conscripts.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_1_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>Expanded slums are unregulated, violence-filled cesspools where gangs battle to control strategic districts. Simply surviving their harsh conditions is all the warrior training one requires.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_2_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Their brains must have shrunk to accommodate their muscles because these dumb brutes need little more than four bare walls. A place to sleep, some iron to pump, and immense quantities of protein-rich food, and they're as happy as a tickled piglet. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_2_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>Even the dumbest party members ridiculed the idea that brainless meat boys could care for their new high-tech gear and weapons. So for every Meatboy in combat, there's a whole pit crew tending to them.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_3_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Loyal Hammerites are extensions of the Supreme Leader's fist, especially when it comes to crushing insurrections. Unsurprisingly, their barracks are a fortress capable of withstanding a siege by the entire city militia.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- JB: still original text -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_3_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>An experienced base commander knows that the famous loyalty of the Hammerites is not as uncompromising as the propaganda claims. In old Fossoria, Hammerite Lords played a vital role in every successful putsch ever committed.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

                                                                                                                     <!-- Chris: Not sure about middle sentence meaning here; JB: recombined all versions -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_4_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>In colonies located deep in Fossorian territory where security is not such a pressing matter, similar workshops produce similar but quite benign machines. Someone was likely promoted - or shot for the redesign.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <!-- For Chris: texts CHECKED in round 0 :) END -->


            <!-- For Chris: feel free to skip -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACULTY_BIO_LORE</LocID>        <!--NOT IN DEMO--> <Text>A cracked aquarium containing alien flesh-eating fungus? A half-empty tank of mutageous gas lying in the middle of the corridor? Always just one step away from a catastrophic containment failure. Nothing new for biology labs the Universe over.  </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_FACULTY_PSY_LORE</LocID>        <!--NOT IN DEMO--> <Text>Psychotronics. Serious scientists usually ridicule the topic. Primals' technology though too often exceeds the limits of possible. An ugly duckling of science became a pretty chick and everyone would like a piece for themselves.   </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>

            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_IRON_GATE_LORE</LocID><!--NOT IN DEMO--> <Text>All walls are dual-purpose. Stop potential intruders and prevent citizens from leaving unchecked. (Or leaving at all.) A snug belt of limerite-reinforced concrete containment.  </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_TRENCH_LORE</LocID>   <!--NOT IN DEMO--> <Text>If Fossorians are good at anything, it's digging. Spicing the whole thing up with heads on spikes seems like a wonderful idea. Sprinkle a few corpses throughout the trenches, icing on the cake. Voila a masterpiece. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_DEFENSIVE_TURRET_LORE</LocID>   <!--NOT IN DEMO--> <Text>The technology was "liberated" from UNSS warehouses. On the downside, recalibrating the recognition software has cost the lives of a boatload of test subjects. The bright side? Test subjects are a renewable resource.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>


            <!-- For Chris: texts ready for proofreading START -->
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_4_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>Supply chains between Fossorian bases usually work only on paper. Therefore if you want to shoot a high volume of sophisticated munitions like underground torpedoes, the best way is to become self-sufficient.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_5_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Carefully designed to keep these ferocious invertebrates under control or at least separated from the rest of the city. Until certain glands are surgically removed from their body, they are untamable.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_5_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>These armored worms are priceless in combat, but becoming their caretaker is a perilous career choice. What's more, it's often made by some inner party members as a less public way to get rid of someone. Two birds, ... </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_6_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Unsurprisingly, very few commissars survived the escape from the old Fossoria. Thanks to the "colorful" composition of the Fossorian army, there is immense pressure to train new ones to ensure that units stay in line.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_6_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>A true idealist always does the most damage. The best way to ensure that the damage gets dealt to the enemy is to keep the commissars in the field. Once they get bored, they start to see traitors everywhere. </Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_7_LORE</LocID>                             <Text>Every finished Liberator is a monument honoring the dedication and sacrifice of Fossorian workers. Truth be told, it's threats and violence that keep their spirits high.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <GameDBLocalizedString>         <LocID>BUILDING_MOLES_SPAWNER_7_UPG_LORE</LocID>                         <Text>All toxic waste from the base is repurposed here to fill the tanks of the Liberator. Many workers handling the devilish cocktail bear mutation marks and are forbidden from accessing the outer base.</Text>  </GameDBLocalizedString>
            <!-- For Chris: texts ready for proofreading END -->

